<h2>Description of heat exchangers</h2>

<TABLE WIDTH=100%><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP> 
<p>Originally designed and built by the
department for ATSR-1 AND ATSR-2 TEST AND CALIBRATION (1) the
<strong>LN2-cooled heat-exchangers</strong>, Fig 1, and re-circulating
fluid loops provide exceptionally uniform cold wall temperatures and
fast response times.</p>

<p>The heat-transfer fluid, Galden HT100, is cooled by pushing it
through an LN2-cooled heat-exchanger element using a high mass flow
rate centrifugal pump. The cooled fluid is then passed through a
powerful in-line heater before entering the vacuum chamber where it is
piped to the distribution manifolds for the cold walls. The return
fluid is then passed back to the heat-exchanger, via manifolds and
feedthroughs, where it is again cooled.</p>

<p>The design of the heat-exchanger element allows for variable
cooling power and economy of use. For steady state conditions the
cooling power is fixed at a low value and the temperature controlled
via the in-line heater. The large working range (-60 C to + 60 C) and
the fast cooling rates achieved (typically 3 K/minute) for the
configuration use during ATSR-1 and ATSR-2 Test and Calibration, Fig 2
and Fig 3, permitted the simulation of orbital heat fluxes to high
accuracy , Fig 4.</p>
